def: A water newt. [Scot. & North of Eng.]
Capable of being worked, or worth working; as, a workable mine;workable clay.
An animal having eight feet, as a spider.
That may be plucked off, cropped, or torn away. [Obs.] Bailey.
A tribe of Indians formerly inhabiting what is now a part ofthe State of New York. They were the central or head tribe of theFive Nations.
An instrument for measuring the bleaching power of chloride oflime and potash; a chlorometer. Ure.
A covering or protection, as a canvas, for a stack.
A room, attached to any place of public resort, where cloaks,overcoats, etc., may be deposited for a time.
One who, or that which, suspends; esp., one of a pair of strapsor braces worn over the shoulders, for holding up the trousers.
Acting or moving automatically by means of compressed air.
The largest of the different kinds of drums, having two heads,and emitting a deep, grave sound. See Bass, a.
The act of weeping noisily.He spake well save that his blubbering interrupted him. Winthrop.
